06126nam a22007095i 9780774855426DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748554267 a10.59962/97807748554262doi  a(DE-B1597)662139  a(OCoLC)1397964970  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHD75.8.D49 2007eb 7aSOC0420002bisacsh04a306.300aDevelopment's Displacements :bEconomies, Ecologies, and Cultures at Risk /ced. by Peter Vandergeest, Pablo Idahosa, Pablo S. Bose. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tDisplacement, Multinationals, and the State -- tWho Defines Displacement? The Operation of the World Bank Involuntary Resettlement Policy in a Large Mining Project -- tGendered Implications: Development-Induced Displacement in Sudan -- tUprooting Communities and Reconfiguring Rural Landscapes: Industrial Tree Plantations and Displacement in Sarawak, Malaysia, and Eastern Thailand -- tDisplacement and Neoliberalism -- tEnforcement and/or Empowerment? Different Displacements Induced by Neoliberal Water Policies in Thailand -- tDisplacements in Neoliberal Land Reforms: Producing Tenure (In)Securities in Laos and Thailand -- tContested Territories: Development, Displacement, and Social Movements in Colombia -- tDams, Development, and Displacement: The Narmada Valley Development Projects -- tConservation and Displacement -- tUpon Whose Terms? The Displacement of Afro-Descendent Communities in the Creation of Costa Rica’s National Parks -- tEntanglements: Campesino and Indigenous Tenure Insecurities on the Honduran North Coast -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs multilateral agencies, social movements, and state authorities worldwide struggle to cope with the effects of large-scale development projects, such as dam building, mining, oil extraction, forest plantations, and nature conservation, the problem of displacement remains unresolved. The crisis of "development refugees" -- those forced to relocate not by wars or political conflicts but rather because of development policies, programs, and projects � is becoming increasingly prevalent across the globe. While existing studies on development-induced displacement have focused on issues such as resettlement and compensation for those displaced, this volume seeks to address displacement as a broad and multilayered phenomenon. A series of illustrative case studies drawn from around the globe provide causal accounts of why and how displacement occurs, what its effects on communities, ecosystems, and economies look like, and the normative or ethical positions held by key actors involved. Contributors offer economic, political, and cultural analyses, as well as extensive ethnographic field research, to present a picture of displacement that illustrates the depth and the breadth of the issue.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic development projectsxEnvironmental aspectsvCase studies. 0aEconomic development projectsxSocial aspectsvCase studies. 0aInternally displaced personsvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Developing & Emerging Countries.2bisacsh1 aBarney, Keith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBose, Pablo S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBose, Pablo S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGruner, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIdahosa, Pablo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab